06363nam a22007815i 9780813553368DE-B159720200623100627.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200623t20122012nju    fo  d z      eng d  a2011023491  a97808135533687 a10.36019/97808135533682doi  a(DE-B1597)530418  a(OCoLC)781542953  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ00aGN289b.G463 2012 4aGN289b.G463 2012 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a611/.018166322300aGenetics and the Unsettled Past :bThe Collision of DNA, Race, and History /cCatherine Lee, Keith Wailoo, Alondra Nelson. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[2012] 4cÂ©2012  a1 online resource (370 p.) :b2 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aRutgers Studies on Race and Ethnicity00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tIntroduction: Genetic Claims and the Unsettled Past -- t1. Who Am I? Genes and the Problem of Historical Identity -- t2. Reconciliation Projects: From Kinship to Justice -- t3. The Unspoken Significance of Gender in Constructing Kinship, Race, and Nation -- t4. A Biologist's Perspective on DNA and Race in the Genomics Era -- t5. The Dilemma of Classification: The Past in the Present -- t6. The Informationalization of Race: Communication, Databases, and the Digital Coding of the Genome -- t7. Forensic DNA Phenotyping: Continuity and Change in the History of Race, Genetics, and Policing -- t8. Forensic DNA and the Inertial Power of Race in American Legal Practice -- t9. Making History via DNA, Making DNA from History: Deconstructing the Race-Disease Connection in Admixture Mapping -- t10. Waiting on the Promise of Prescribing Precision: Race in the Era of Pharmacogenomics -- t11. French Families, Paper Facts: Genetics, Nation, and Explanation -- t12. Categorization, Census, and Multiculturalism: Molecular Politics and the Material of Nation -- t13. "It's a Living History, Told by the Real Survivors of the Times-DNA": Anthropological Genetics in the Tradition of Biology as Applied History -- t14. Cells, Genes, and Stories: HeLa's Journey from Labs to Literature -- t15. The Case of the Genetic Ancestor -- t16. Making Sense of Genetics, Culture, and History: A Case Study of a Native Youth Education Program -- t17. Humanitarian DNA Identification in Post-Apartheid South Africa -- t18. Forbidden or Forsaken? The (Mis)Use of a Forbidden Knowledge Argument in Research on Race, DNA, and Disease -- t19. Genetic Claims and Credibility: Revisiting History and Remaking Race -- tCONTRIBUTORS -- tINDEX 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOur genetic markers have come to be regarded as portals to the past. Analysis of these markers is increasingly used to tell the story of human migration; to investigate and judge issues of social membership and kinship; to rewrite history and collective memory; to right past wrongs and to arbitrate legal claims and human rights controversies; and to open new thinking about health and well-being. At the same time, in many societies genetic evidence is being called upon to perform a kind of racially charged cultural work: to repair the racial past and to transform scholarly and popular opinion about the "nature" of identity in the present. Genetics and the Unsettled Past considers the alignment of genetic science with commercial genealogy, with legal and forensic developments, and with pharmaceutical innovation to examine how these trends lend renewed authority to biological understandings of race and history. This unique collection brings together scholars from a wide range of disciplines-biology, history, cultural studies, law, medicine, anthropology, ethnic studies, sociology-to explore the emerging and often contested connections among race, DNA, and history. Written for a general audience, the book's essays touch upon a variety of topics, including the rise and implications of DNA in genealogy, law, and other fields; the cultural and political uses and misuses of genetic information; the way in which DNA testing is reshaping understandings of group identity for French Canadians, Native Americans, South Africans, and many others within and across cultural and national boundaries; and the sweeping implications of genetics for society today.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jun 2020) 0aEthnicity. 0aGene mapping. 0aGenetic markers. 0aGenomics. 0aHuman population genetics. 0aRace. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aLee, Catherine, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aNelson, Alondra, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aWailoo, Keith, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311068861008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066331040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813553368423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780813553368.jpg  a978-3-11-066331-0  RUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-068861-0  RUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK